 persistence of these concepts in our world today.Key Features Discusses the recent scholarly interest in classical representations in popular culture Looks at how both Greco-Roman epic and Western film in general help to define foundational ideologies for their respective culturesIncludes case studies of four films – Howard Hawks’ Red River (1948), Fred Zinnemann’s High Noon (1952), George Stevens’ Shane (1953), and John Ford’s The Searchers (1956) – which analyze specific affinities with the Homeric epics and Virgil’s AeneidExamines John Ford’s The Man Who Shot Liberty Valance (1962) as an Oedipal drama, in relation to Greek and Roman epic  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCowboys in popular culturezUnited States. 0aCowboys in popular culture; United States. 0aEpic poetry, GreekxHistory and criticism. 0aEpic poetry, Greek. 0aHeroes. 0aWestern filmszUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aWestern films; United States; History and criticism. 4aClassics & Ancient History. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311078044440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781474402477zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781474402477423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781474402477/original  a978-3-11-078044-4  Edinburgh University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK